<div class="wrapper-content">
  <div class="full-up formatting">
    <h2>On the Shoulders of Giants</h2>
    <p>Modern applications are a culmination of past knowledge. They are an assemblage of discrete pieces. The open source movement formalized the path for people to share and re-use these pieces &mdash;packages&mdash; with the goal of accelerating product development. Makers spend less time re-building boilerplate and instead dedicate themselves to creating real value. Thus resulting in mature software coming to market in less time.
</p>

    <p>At scale, open source looks like millions of engineers & designers packaging discrete pieces of functionality and sharing it via the internet. In order to fully discover and re-use this shared knowledge it needs to be structured. Enter package managers, who seek to index the pieces of an open source ecosystem to facilitate discovery and growth of that ecosystem. When we realized that package management didn’t exist for one of the javascript frameworks we use to build products (Meteor) we created Atmosphere.</p>
  </div>
</div>

